Now I have everything I need. Here is the complete, step-by-step implementation plan.

---

## Custom Theme System: Implementation Plan

### Architecture Decision: `data-theme` attribute + CSS blocks (Option C)

Set `data-theme="t3-dark"` (etc.) on `<html>` via `applyTheme()` in the existing `useTheme` hook. Add one CSS block per named theme in `index.css`. The `.dark` class mechanism stays completely untouched — it's what `@variant dark` reads, and `DiffWorkerPoolProvider` only reads `resolvedTheme: "light" | "dark"`, which continues to work.

No JS-driven `style.setProperty()` loops, no new build config, no new dependencies.

---

### Step 1 — `packages/shared/src/theme.ts` (new file)

Pure TypeScript, no Effect imports needed. Define:

```ts
export type ThemeId = "t3-light" | "t3-dark" | "t3-midnight";

export interface ThemeColorSlots {
  background: string;
  foreground: string;
  primary: string;
  sidebar: string;
  editor: string;
  terminal: string;
  statusBar: string;
}

export interface ThemeDefinition {
  id: ThemeId;
  label: string;
  resolvedMode: "light" | "dark";
  colors: ThemeColorSlots;
  // CSS variable overrides applied on :root when this theme is active.
  // Values are complete CSS color expressions (hex, oklch, color-mix, etc.)
  cssVars: Partial<Record<string, string>>;
}

export const BUILT_IN_THEMES: readonly ThemeDefinition[] = [ ... ];
export const THEME_IDS: readonly ThemeId[] = BUILT_IN_THEMES.map((t) => t.id);
```

**`ThemeColorSlots` rationale:** The `colors` object holds the swatch preview values (plain hex or oklch). The `cssVars` record holds the actual CSS variable overrides keyed by the CSS var name without `--` prefix (e.g. `"background"`, `"primary"`, `"ring"`). These two concerns are kept separate so the `ThemeSelector` can read `colors` without parsing CSS expressions.

**The three built-in themes:**

| `id` | `label` | `resolvedMode` | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| `"t3-light"` | "T3 Light" | `"light"` | Same palette as current `:root` light defaults — keeps backward compat for existing `system` users |
| `"t3-dark"` | "T3 Dark" | `"dark"` | Same palette as current `@variant dark` defaults |
